United States: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is even comical to see the persistent effort by the wise President Barack Obama to replicate his predecessor's strategy on the Afghan issue, which he himself considered simple.
When he finally let his long-awaited doctrine seep through, it turned out that he had carbon-copied it from Bush's Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not content with using the phrase 'as in Iraq' several times in the same text, he did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's speech in January 2007 as the title of his own speech: 'A new way forward'.
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush's idea of sending new reinforcements to a civil war-torn Iraq as "irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences".
The following months, however, have shown that Bush's strategy, which was based on the recommendations of the field commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the newspapers are not talking about Iraq at the moment.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, but objectively speaking, it left his successor with a much more favorable end-state than could have been hoped for.
Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again in Afghanistan
Again, it was the field commanders who asked him for an increase in the military contingent, including the Afghan operation commander, General Stanley McCristal, who even sharply criticized the reluctance of the White House despite the subordination habits.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months, but for lack of a better option, he at least swindled the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He succeeded in extracting the promise of an additional 5 000 from Europe, although he had originally counted on 10 000.
The most problematic part of Obama's strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the troops from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete the process within three years. The entire Obama doctrine raises more questions than it answers.
Many doubt that a halving will produce the same results as the increase in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out for the exact opposite - no one can be trusted and no treaties are respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, who are used to changing leaders day after day as they see fit.
Political institutions, though officially established, will remain as dust behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is particularly difficult to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in the absence of clarity in the relations, which are further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "state of readiness", which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy is perplexing because of its voluntarism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and is now on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and unrealistic heart can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the turmoil of war for their "prompt homecoming" will bring a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for troop withdrawal is purely irresponsible as the Taliban will see it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the European will to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is turning negative.
European politicians do not know or do not want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor which could radically alter the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and if the increased sanctions do not have an effect on the Iranians, the Americans will be faced with the very difficult question of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
It will be necessary to answer this question, for example, when, according to Obama, America will have successfully withdrawn its troops from Afghanistan.
Any such solution, however, will result in a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only downside for Obama is that he has three years until the presidential election and therefore has plenty of time to work out a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
