Czech discovery: a substance that works on HIV viruses 'enduring' too
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow down the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to the drugs.
This reality in some cases overrides the fact that the combination does not act as strongly on common variants of the virus as well as some already available drugs.
There is no cure for AIDS at this time.
However, the lives of patients can be dramatically prolonged by a combination of drugs that prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body.
However, their use has a number of side effects.
In addition, suppression of this multiplication results in the development of so-called drug-resistant viruses, which are no longer resistant to drugs.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg, paves the way for a way of dealing with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metallocarbons are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the growth of the virus in a way that is different from any drug that has been used so far and that's why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their binding to the virus proteins.
Metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein in the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
Stopping the HIV protease also stops the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the researchers explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In their paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of combinations in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable.
The efficacy of this series of substances on HIV proteases was tested in test tubes and in resistant variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metallocarboranes on the current version of the enzyme is not as strong as on clinical drugs, but it does not weaken on the resistant versions against which current drugs are often ineffective.
