Westerners mistakenly view the one-child policy as a rights issue, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
It's true, they're robbing us of the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the head of human resources, said she only wanted one child because she was an only child herself. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone looking out for us".
We are not used to taking care of someone else and we really do not want to take care of others".
Chen Zijian, 42, owner of a translation company, said it more bluntly.
For the middle-class, working-class couples who are driving down the birth rate, he says, you have to be selfish to succeed.
People in their 20s and 30s grew up seeing their parents struggle in the early days of capitalist China and don't want to have that lifestyle themselves, he says.
Even a single child requires a lot of time from his parents, he said.
A mother has to give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there's the space issues -- "You need to change your apartment" -- and the planning -- "When your child is only nine months old, you need to write his resume to get a place in the best kindergarten".
Most of his friends are willing to do this experiment once, Chen says, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to benefit from a higher standard of living, he says.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
The UN group has draft plans for reducing emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized so far by disorganized allocations and mutual recriminations -- came back into the spotlight on Friday, as a document was released highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations shouldering most of the burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as a major breakthrough in the time-strapped negotiations, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
The text, drafted by a special UN working group, does not say how much the rich countries would give to the poor to help with global warming, both in the short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed and emerging economies could reduce their carbon output and what would be the upper limit of global temperature rise that policymakers would be willing to tolerate.
It gives the process a great deal of flexibility, said John Coequyt, the Sierra Club's Washington representative.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's Executive Secretary for Climate Change, Yvo de Boer, described as "the full picture".
It shows the guidelines of a possible agreement in which the industrialized nations would collectively reduce their emissions in 2020 by 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce theirs by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched the negotiations on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion per year for the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to cope with floods and droughts or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, the US representative at the climate negotiations, rejected any discussion of forcing industrialized countries to reduce greenhouse gases, compared to the voluntary efforts of the major emerging economies, if they were not financed by developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration is becoming tougher on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The US will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the main developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not insist enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern's comments came an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei said the top US negotiator either lacked "common sense" or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the US would not give China financial aid to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and the emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States bickering over their respective obligations while the poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the major powers were fighting over who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though the vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold the major emitters accountable for their actions.
It is really a game in which a new economic hegemony is being developed", said Ulate, who is also the Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries that are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that the negotiations will lead to at least a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drew up a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of the European Commission's Climate Unit, said that the action of small island states has "put political pressure on the whole political process", partly because they are now unified and calling on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The debate became a matter of urgency as delegates focused on the need to resolve most of the outstanding issues before the heads of government could reach an agreement.
High-level officials such as India's environment minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese vice minister stepped off their planes and rushed to the Bella Center building for closed-door meetings and briefings, so that they could make claims that would be considered over the next week.
The real image of the rally -- where 13,000 people come in and out of the convention center every day -- activists playing guitar performing late-night shows mocking countries that they say are betraying each other and proposals being written and distributed on paper instead of emails -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and by Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
"We are entering the court of the great", said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
In Britain, the first train at 140 miles an hour will redefine Monday syndrome.
At 5:13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle will go through the night to signal the departure of a train that will mark a revolution in transportation in Britain.
The country's first high-speed commuter train will reach 140 miles per hour as it runs from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering the 93 miles in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister of Transport, will be joined by Lady Kelly Holmes on board the first Javelin commuter train out of London.
He hopes the new service will allow Britain to join an international network of fast and reliable trains and link the major conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
Small lost holes will become thriving suburban cities, business travel times will be much shorter, and the switch from airplanes and cars to trains will reduce national carbon emissions while reducing traffic jams on the roads.
In theory, all three main political parties are in favour of this project.
But the £10 billion needed to build a new railway network, the inevitable planning battle and fears of environmental hazards are likely to hold back Britain's high-speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to produce a feasibility report for the government, will hand over its document to Lord Adonis on December 30.
This will enable it to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next stage planned for the high-speed network.
The new line from London to the West Midlands will be drawn within five metres of the urban area and sites where the impact on the environment may be controversial.
In the countryside, the plan will be drawn up to 25 metres from the final route.
It is also planned that HS2 will present three options for a larger high-speed network, going north.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
The preferred options are highlighted in a Y configuration for which a high speed line will go all the way to the West Midlands.
The line will split in two at or near Birmingham, with one branch going west of the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another going north-east, to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will run through Scotland.
'It seems that this will be the best option for performance' said a rail professional.
When this is completed, the journey time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first branch, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to a one-hour journey today.
The proposals will allow the train to travel at 400km/h, making the UK's network the fastest in the world.
The initial track is designed to allow trains of 400m length and carrying 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can run on a London to Birmingham line.
A terminal with a capacity of 20,000 passengers per hour would be required.
Due to space constraints, it is planned that an existing station will be enlarged to accommodate the high-speed network.
Railway industry experts say that only St Pancras International or Euston offer this possibility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the project should go ahead, but longer public consultations and planning procedures mean a final decision will not be made until after a general election.
Even if he launches the machine, the network will have to be built piece by piece.
Trains will first be forced off the high-speed lines on the existing track north of Birmingham, keeping journey times between London and Scotland to over three hours.
This seems to be the best solution for a switch from airplanes to trains, and it is a point of reference for the railway revolution.
Taxpayers pay back £75,000 loan for Tory orangery
Alan Duncan, the leading Tory MP, has charged the taxpayer thousands of pounds a year to reimburse the cost of an orange grove he built in his constituency home.
The party leader who was demoted by David Cameron for complaining that members of parliament were "kept up", increased his loan by £75,000 to build an oak extension to his second home in Rutland.
He was authorized to charge the taxpayer the extra interest, amounting to hundreds of pounds a month.
The Commons authorities received the complaints at that time and were not questioned by Sir Thomas Legg, who is conducting a Members' Expenditure Review.
Mr Duncan, one of the richest members of Parliament, owns a two-storey house in a village in his Rutland-Melton constituency.
The adjoining houses were sold for almost a million pounds.
The ground floor includes a kitchen, a living room and a dining room, but the memorial office says Mr. Duncan needed more space.
Last year, he added a porch to the house, describing it in his plans as an orange grove.
Neighbors describe it as a "pleasure porch".
Mr Duncan was not asked to explain the increase in borrowing during a recent inquiry by the Commons Privileges and Standards Committee into his previous borrowing arrangements.
The Committee cleared him last month of any charges of non-compliance, following an investigation into his spending.
In 2004, Mr Duncan altered the legal security of the £271,406 loan from his London estate to his constituency house which he had bought in 1991, the year before he became an MP.
Documents released this week show that Mr Duncan was claiming around £1,400 a month in borrowing interest until March last year.
In April, his demands increased by more than £1,800 per month.
The interest rate on Mr Duncan's RBS loan was not changed at that time, suggesting that all the increases were intended to finance the GBP 75000 loan.
The RBS standard variable interest rate went from 7.94 percent in December 2007 to 4 percent in March this year, and has remained unchanged since then.
The latest release from the Commons authorities shows that Mr Duncan was still asking for £1,250 in May.
Mr. Duncan lost his position as Chief of the Shadow Cabinet in September, after an undercover journalist allegedly filmed him declaring that members of parliament had to survive "over budget" after the spending scandal.
"In fact, it's now national, you have to live "on a budget" and you are treated as "of the m...e"
He said, "I spent my money on my garden and I asked for a small share, based on what was right.
And I could have asked for a hell of a lot more, but I didn't".
The MP, a millionaire from his former job as an oil trader, began having to explain his spending in May after it emerged that he had asked for thousands of pounds for his garden, before agreeing with the expenses office that this "could be considered excessive".
An activist dug a £-shaped hole in Mr Duncan's lawn, to protest after it was revealed that he had been asking for £4,000 for three years.
Asked about the loan increase last night, Mr. Duncan said, "It was for capital improvements, approved by both the expense office and then Legg".
He added: "There is no problem with evasion or making up or using the rules or anything.
It was very clear, it was in the rules, it was allowed, and so on.
