By placing the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put market conquest strategies back in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences regularly returns!
The demobilization of employees can lead to a deadly demoralisation.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the outgrowth of a much more general phenomenon which particularly affects managers.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all intellectual functions of the company, particularly R&D and, even more so, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EIS "requires all stakeholders (...) to be proactive and forward-looking"; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that the revenues of authoritarian management are totally opposed.
This is why we are calling for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the centre of the company's concerns as much as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls
Will internal opinion polls - such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees - encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
I'm afraid not, though.
- Firstly, because I have observed that, faced with a new situation, every structure finally, after many detours, comes to do as a priority... what it has always done.
- Secondly, because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of power - grows proportionately to the importance of its own failures.
Well, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
They come from the great engineering schools, and they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviourist theory, recently revived by the American "neuroscience" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to manipulate the "levers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr reinforces the leaders in a mechanistic governance posture, unsuited to today's world.
Identifying and measuring the factors of mobilisation
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises requires the adoption of a finalist view of human behaviour.
It consists in integrating, in all governance reasoning or practice, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it is clearly seen as a means of realizing part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
At present, only the studies from the Motive-action Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their enterprise on the basis of a predetermined dose which allows them, through their perceived image of the enterprise, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their life plans.
By identifying and measuring these mobilisation factors, business managers can monitor, forecast and anticipate their 'social performance' and put their human resource management 'in the right place'.
They thus create a favourable environment for the concerted development of a robust and efficient economic intelligence.
Oslo speech: Obama's "just war" is worthy of praise on the right
The US right wing on Friday welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo the day before, saying it was satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize laureate had defended the concept of "just war" against America's enemies.
The conservatives, who had flown the award to Mr Obama on October 9, applauded the presidential speech this time, as did Sarah Palin, former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said", Palin, a right-wing Republican, told USA Today, adding that she herself had addressed the topic of "sometimes necessary" war in her recently published memoir.
War is, of course, the last thing I think the Americans want to have to do, but it's necessary.
She said that these terrorists had to be stopped.
Obama, who inherited his predecessor George W. Bush's two wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, spent Thursday in Oslo justifying the use of force, a way of explaining his decision to send 30,000 additional troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Mr. Obama, Newt Gingrich, said that the president had done a "very good job" in Oslo.
I thought the speech was really very good, said the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential speech.
In some ways, I found this speech quite historic, Mr. Gingrich said in an interview on the radio program "The Takeaway".
The former candidate, considered by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a leftist president" remind the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not give a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
For Michael Gerson, a former George W. Bush aide turned Washington Post columnist, Mr. Obama delivered "a very American speech".
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does", "he spoke like an American president", reminding Europeans "that they live in a security bubble that they did not create and that they do little to preserve it", said Mr Gerson.
Among the few on the right who were not convinced, a hawk of the Bush era, former UN ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "deadening, bombastic and uninspiring" on the National Review Online website.
To the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When war is wrapped up in the notion of justice, it can easily be justified in the slaughter of innocents, he warned.
The centre-left press, however, remained eloquent about the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to believe that the Nobel was prematurely awarded to Mr. Obama, called his speech "a super-production" even for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech "should serve as a road map for international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression", the California newspaper wrote.
Mr. Obama "gave the speech he needed", said the New York Times, calling it "dark and edifying at the same time".
Roadsters: three marathons for a deal that saves Christmas supplies
After three marathon negotiations, the road unions and the TLF, the only employers' organisation to have stayed to the end, reached an agreement on Friday evening that ends the strike order and the threat to Christmas supplies.
At the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, "rejoiced" at this agreement, after several negotiating sessions, which began on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, the negotiators left early Friday morning, hoping to sign the text of the agreement quickly by the end of the morning.
This was despite the fact that three employers' organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slammed the door.
But it took more than six hours of a meeting that started at 11:00 a.m. for everyone to agree and at 6:00 p.m. the text was signed.
The conflict "would have been very damaging to businesses" and "there was a fear that it would disrupt the end-of-year celebrations", Mr Bussereau said.
The text provides for a 4% increase in wages for the lowest paid (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest paid (international transport).
The hourly rate for low-wage workers is being reduced from 8.72 euros to 9.06 euros.
It is not much, but we have come a long way, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
Either we give the order to our militants that there are no blockades, no blockades of the supply centers.
But there can always be some recalcitrants who are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of the TLF, welcomed "a good agreement", although it was "difficult to concede the increases on high salaries in view of international competition".
According to him, the increases will be in the order of 170 euros a month for low-wage workers and 100 to 120 euros for the highest-wage workers.
The agreement was a compromise between common sense and respect for employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed "a historic agreement".
The Commission's proposal was to be submitted to the Council.
The agreement also provides for the increase in travel costs by 3% and the general state of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will make it possible to address the issue of a 13th month and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Mr Bussereau recalled that "a €100 million reduction in employer charges" was the subject of a government amendment to the draft amending finance bill for 2009, voted on Thursday night by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote on it "in the same terms".
The signature of the TLF enables the agreement to apply initially to the companies belonging to this organization and, in the second stage, to the whole profession, in the event of an extension by the Minister of Labour.
The Commission's proposal was to be submitted to the Council by the end of the year.
Opposition from employers' organisations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "deceitful market", as the 100 million euros "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport has forced us to negotiate in a hurry, not as a conclusion to a shared analysis, but to avoid upsetting the turkey-eaters of the next Christmas Eve, lamented Unostra.
The other said that the agreement "could be the death knell for a very large number of SMEs in the sector over the next 12 months".
RER A: disruptions this weekend, unions unhappy with RATP's proposals
The disruptions on the RER A, France's largest urban public transportation line, will continue over the weekend, as a meeting on Friday on the second day of the strike between the unions and the RATP management has left them on their hunger for their premium demand.
