This is not what drivers want, who demand a fair premium, according to Thierry Garon (South).
The RATP even put its bonus proposals in parentheses, the CGT was indignant, stressing that the management "was not in a position to solve a problem whereas the road hauliers and the SNCF have done so".
A further meeting is scheduled for Monday to "examine more broadly the conditions of the profession", RATP said.
This also led the unions to say that the company "made fun of weekend users".
By morning, some 150 motorists had stormed a settlement committee at headquarters in Paris.
It was then that the management, which had refused to discuss the strike until then, suggested the meeting "in order to appease the situation".
The conflict threatens to spread to RER B on Tuesday, after the filing of a notice by Unsa and Independents.
The unions are demanding a premium of 120 euros (Unsa) to 150 euros including 30 euros variable (CGT, FO, CFDT, South, Independent) and complain about the deterioration of working conditions on this line to the daily million of passengers.
RER drivers, all in the second half of their careers, receive a gross of 2,200 to 2,700 euros and bonuses of 600 to 650 euros for shiftwork on Sundays and holidays.
Turkey's courts dissolve pro-Kurdish party, decision with heavy consequences
Turkey's constitutional court on Friday dissolved the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by angry protests in the Kurdish community in the country's southeast and in Istanbul.
This decision is likely to greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "focus of activities detrimental to the independence of the State and its indivisible unity", the Court's President Hasim Kiliç told the press after four days of deliberations.
The decision was made unanimously by all 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to pronounce the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's cadres, including its chairman Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity of Mr Türk and Mrs Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's assets.
The DTP has 21 seats in the parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament rather than sit as un-labelled MPs.
The decision follows a 2007 case brought by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accused the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party, however, insists it has "no organic links" with the PKK but refuses to label it a terrorist organisation and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court's ruling comes as the government has just reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen its rights in an attempt to stem Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leaders had claimed that a dissolution could lead to a renewed escalation of tensions in Southeastern Anatolia, where numerous protests against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have escalated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
As soon as the justice was announced, a thousand protesters gathered outside the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, the large city in the southeast of the country with a majority of Kurds.
Police fired tear gas and water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails and stones with fronds.
A hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk said that the court's decision would "deepen the despair".
The European Union is also committed to the development of the internal market and to the promotion of the free movement of goods.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed to the closure of political parties.
This is not a solution, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a complete torpedoing of the democratic opening initiated by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
He also called for the EU to be involved in the negotiations with the countries of the region.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snow may fall
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a very harsh winter.
But the head of the road cleaning and sanding service (FES) clarifies that this is not to annoy citizens.
It's simply so that the agents can test the vehicles' technology and learn how to master them.
And according to the weatherman, it could be as early as this weekend.
Over 300 officers and 120 vehicles are standing by to tackle the snow and ice.
The FES is following a very elaborate plan here.
Mr Brauburger explains that as soon as it starts to snow in the city of Frankfurt and the temperatures drop below zero, large sandblasting vehicles travel along 20 main routes (called routes A).
This includes the high traffic streets, the main arteries, such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire accesses, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as the Atzelbergstraße.
The FES officers start their shift at three in the morning.
If necessary, the 1040 kilometres of road must be salted with road salt that adheres well, in a maximum of 3 hours.
This is why the FES service starts at 3am "so that the roads are cleared when the daily migration traffic starts".
The hardest part is when the snow starts to fall at 7:30 in the morning.
This is a problem, says the head of the road cleaning and sanding department, "because no motorists are willing to let the salting vehicles pass".
Then, when the snow is gone, we take care of the access roads and the access roads - like the Rat-Beil-Straße.
Secondary roads and side streets come last.
Mr Brauburger knows that there are always some complaints about this.
At five o'clock in the morning, the FES's foot team sets off to identify the areas deemed dangerous and the crossings as a priority.
As for the cycle paths, the FES services are generally not able to take care of them.
Mr Brauburger said that there is a special service in Frankfurt which monitors the condition of bridges between 10pm and 4.30am.
As ice forms very quickly on these surfaces, salting vehicles are called upon as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees Celsius.
The police also sometimes call upon this special service in case of need.
The cradle of the dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: it was about 2 meters long and 1.5 meters high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was equipped with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended in sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues report in Thursday's Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to exhibit these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which was then part of the upper land of the supercontinent Pangea, and was located near the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
It provides information about the relationships, distribution, and characteristics of the family.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt began excavating with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Natural History Museum of Utah and a member of the excavation team says that they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating back to the Triassic.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations have uncovered the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that supports theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi word for the sun god.
Sterling Nesbitt called the find exceptional: fossils of dinosaurs from the Triassic period are extremely rare, limited to a few fragments of incomplete bones.
Not all paleontologists share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not think that the discovery is particularly spectacular, but he does say that it confirms some theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making classification of the earliest dinosaurs very difficult.
Experts wonder when the saurians split into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores), which include the later tyrannosaurs and velociraptors, from which birds descended; the sauropods, long-necked quadrupeds and their relatives; and the ornithischians, which include species such as the triceratops and the stegosaurs.
According to studies by S. Nesbitt and colleagues, the Tawa is one of the earliest theropods.
This species has an interesting mix of both primitive and developed features, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers have found evidence that suggests the Tawa hallae had small air sacs in their skull bones, just like the birds that are the descendants of theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe than for mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the huge sauropods also possessed air sacs and a lightweight skeleton, it can be assumed that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
Since the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers have concluded that the saphenous snake originated there.
So the three great lines of evolution split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, which is the whole of the emergent land that was the supercontinent of Pangea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the paleontology team also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot have descended from a common ancestor who migrated, the researchers suggest.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of the magazine Science Studies says that there have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Paleontologist Martin Sander in Bonn says that there is an even older species, the silesaurus, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to the dinosaurs.
He said this could be misleading because there are a lot of dinosaur fossils preserved in South America, and there are almost none on other continents.
But how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapod of the Second Age from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch is still a mystery.
In the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and many other saurians.
By the end of the Triassic dinosaurs had spread across the planet, fostering the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not permanent.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction in which dinosaurs survived in a random way while other reptiles would have died out.
Or maybe dinosaurs were better adapted and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
Such success is not permanent.
150 million years later, a meteorite fell on a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and that had since then been in the shadows: the mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are those of professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna, and Berkeley, California.
There are those of lecturers from the Universities of Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
The police evacuation of the casino at the J.W. Goethe University in Frankfurt is making waves all over the planet.
278 professors and teachers from the J.W. Goethe University and other institutions of higher education in Germany, Europe and North and South America express their solidarity with the protesting students of the Westend Campus.
In a statement written in German and English, they condemned the police intervention requested by the university's governing committee.
Last week, the university president, Werner Müller-Estler, ordered the evacuation of the buildings occupied by the striking students and teachers after walls and artworks were smeared with graffiti.
Five students were injured during the evacuation.
The signatories feel that the damage did not justify "such violent intervention by the police commando against the students and teachers who had organized their own classes".
The evacuation represents an "unacceptable infringement" of freedom of research and teaching.
Focusing attention exclusively on acts of vandalism only serves to "delegitimize and criminalize protest" and attempts to make people forget the reasons for the mobilization.
The University Board thus avoided the debate that would have been necessary.
The court officials demand that the criminal proceedings be suspended immediately.
Most of the occupants had no part in the damage.
Legitimacy of the protests
The youth of the service sector union Green and the German Trade Union Confederation (DGB) stand in solidarity with the students.
The protests are only a legitimate expression of growing concern for our own future, says Alexander Klein, regional youth secretary of the Verdi union.
As for the Minister of Science of the State of Hesse Eva Kühne-Hörmann (CDU), she took the case for the action taken by the President of the University and the police.
We thank the President of the University.
Any occupation and degradation of the premises is totally unacceptable, she told the regional parliament of Wiesbaden last Thursday during the TV show Aktuelle Stunde.
We understand the meaning of the protests but do not accept vandalism, said CDU MP Peter Beuth.
The parliamentary groups of the opposition SPD, the Greens and the Left (die Linke) did not share this view.
The CSU is using a few painted walls as a pretext to criminalize protests, said Janine Wissler of the Left Party (Linke)
Instead of thinking about the students' arguments and demands, we're evacuating them.
The Left Party has tabled a motion calling on the Minister of the Interior to report on the conditions of the police intervention.
The new Silicon Valley
For a long time it had the reputation of being a secret city, closed to visitors from the West.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was a secret weapons research site under strict surveillance during the Soviet period.
Today, with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the centre of Moscow, the municipality has a reputation as the Soviet Silicon Valley.
Important micro- and nanoelectronics production and research facilities are located there.
As early as September 2008, representatives of Zelenograd established links with the Frankfurt Science Centre Riedberg  and with the university institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There have been reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a  Protocol of Close Collaboration.
The signatories were the deputy mayor of Moscow Yuri Rosljak and the prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz head of project section for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
But also economic relations.
It will enable FIZ companies to enter the rapidly expanding Russian market.
On the other hand, Russian scientific societies are interested in obtaining contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of famous Soviet research institutes and societies.
The Moscow Institute of Electrical Engineering, the large firms Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika are located here.
The town was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist town" for armament research.
Zelenograd (literal translation  Green City ) takes its name from the forested hills in the heart of which the research centres are located.
The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project is unfathomably large.
For its supporters it is nothing less than the new heart of Europe.
If you want to. S21, it's much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg, in a desperate chaos of construction sites for about ten years.
Stuttgart 21 was born out of the spirit of the 1980s.
The railway stations, with tracks ending in the middle of the city, were reputed at the time to be the relics of 19th century transport technology that were the brake blocks of modern rail traffic because it took a long time to get the locomotives from the rear to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure  that's what you have to do.
That is why the mainline stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart too: a train station, which is about halfway on the Trans-European Main Line between Paris and Budapest/Bratislava, hence the slogan "heart of Europe".
The realisation of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 1980s have long since become incompatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners acknowledged that the cost of burying the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
In fact, the mainline stations no longer pose any real problems of entering and exiting since there are modern, reversible trains with autorels and driver cars at both ends.
However, the construction of Stuttgart 21 is now being launched alongside the new route of the inter-city line to Ulm.
Regional and local policies have won.
The railway company is part of the problem because it is the taxpayer who pays the cost of the risks of the largest infrastructure project in the Federal Republic and not the public company.
From the urban point of view, this project is relatively well justified.
You get an urban space that - if you believe the computer-generated planners' graphics - will be very green.
S21 is harmful to the rail transport system.
The passing station and the extension of the section are designed for a traffic of people to which - and this is typical of the 1980s - enormous growth was attributed.
At that time there was no competition for low-cost flights.
Modern traffic policy should first focus on strengthening freight traffic as rail transport is much more environmentally friendly than road transport by truck.
But the new line, with its slopes, is not suitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious, indirectly affects many other railway projects.
For example, €6 billion will be spent on the Swabia project.
That's the official figure.
Some experts believe that ten to fifteen billion is more realistic.
One thing is certain, in the next decade this money will be lacking for other interconnection and congestion points in the network.
The list of the Ministry of Transport mentions 60 major projects in all.
One of the most important is the extension of the section across the Rhine valley by a good 180 kilometres.
Since 1987 this line has been built in slow motion.
It would be really urgent to press the mushroom here all the way.
But the S21 project is a brake pad.
The Rhine Valley route is becoming a bottleneck for international goods traffic in the heart of Europe.
Government reviews airport ruling
In the regional parliament in Wiesbaden, the Land government raised the possibility of appealing the judgment of the Hesse Administrative Court concerning the ban on night flights.
The Minister of Economic Affairs Dieter Posch (FDP) announced that the CDU/FDP coalition had commissioned experts to examine the Administrative Tribunal's judgment from a legal point of view, which is a document of over 400 pages.
The Kassel Court had justified in a written document that the Land should adapt the regulations on the prohibition of night flights in the event that the project for the construction of the north-west runway at Frankfurt airport was implemented.
The authorization to land 17 aircraft between 11 p.m. and 5 a.m., as envisaged by the Land government, is not compatible with the legal protection of citizens against nighttime air pollution.
The coalition must have decided by January 4 whether it wishes to appeal against the judgment.
The opposition criticises this delay and tries to put pressure on the government representative to withdraw from the appeal before the Federal Administrative Court in Leipzig.
The leader of the SPD parliamentary group, Torsten Schäfer-Gümbel, calls on the CDU and the FDP to return to their promise made before the elections, which was to ban night flights, otherwise this will be considered a total breach of a given promise.
It is very difficult to be allowed to keep your word, said Green leader Tarek Al-Wazir, referring to the FDP's election slogan "We keep our promises".
Minister Posch refuted the accusations of Schäfer-Gümbel that the Land government was still trying to authorize night flights by using "avocational and blatant methods".
It takes time to do a thorough legal review.
The coalition doesn't want to make a decision based on a "quick first impression".
The decision must be legally reliable, says Stefan Müller (FDP).
The interpretation of the opposition concerning the statements of its group on the prohibition of night flights is completely wrong.
US banks reimburse the aid
The big American banks, hit hard by the crisis, are cutting off their ties to the state.
Bank of America announced on Wednesday that it had paid back $45 billion in full to the Treasury, matching the aid provided under the TARP bailout.
The US television channel CNBC reported that Citigroup was also considering repaying the aid received.
The banking institutions are thus seeking to get rid of the restrictions imposed on the acceptance of sums, such as the limitation of bonuses to executives and the payment of higher fees.
Bank of America launched a capital increase by selling securities to investors that brought it $19 billion in fresh cash.
The remainder of the sum comes from the bank's coffers which are well filled up by the sale of several branches in other sectors.
Last Wednesday night, Bank of America CEO Kenneth Lewis specifically thanked the American taxpayer: the capital injection has helped tremendously to get through a difficult time.
