Oneiroid experiences are highly complex semi-dreams which are perceived as real by the person experiencing them and which he cannot distinguish from the dream even when he is in a waking state.
The state of oniroid consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies such as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully conscious, but experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that affects his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It's a mental boundary state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation which is intolerable in itself, a capacity for organization which is given to us, to us men, so as not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
It's all real even in later memories.
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his dreamlike experiences in his book "Change of Heart" as a soul-saving action.
He is 49 years old, and at the time of his departure, he is conscious and on a journey of several days after a heart valve operation followed by a transplant; during this time, his body is condemned to remain immobile in intensive care.
Claussen immerses himself in a world he has created from scratch, visiting strange places, travelling through time, and seeing himself as an old man in a railway sanatorium, with a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages amongst nobles who manufacture narcotics from blood.
He is kidnapped by a Greek motorcycle driver who takes him back to his country, surfs his hospital bed in the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He becomes completely absorbed in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
"The dream is a very different state", he writes, describing what he experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental travel are extremely vivid and highly detailed even years later.
They are even more distinct and intense than the actual experience.
The intensity of this experience shatters the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, the unerotic delusions, psychosis, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in the waking state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can cause a distortion of what we call reality".
An experience that can also be quite enriching.
