75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generation who want to be mothers.
This is the finding of the study 'Fertility and professional career of women in Spain', carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, which was carried out on 9 737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers saw their professional careers limited by maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of married life and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of employment occupied.
Those who have no activity outside the home, part-time work or have a job with a shaky work schedule, are more likely to get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women in stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay marriage and first pregnancy and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of age with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling into a relationship.This figure rises to 4.1 for those working in the public sector. These data show that women with stable jobs have needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to postpone marriage and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work done has a major influence on maternity, but less on the date of the beginning of a common life, explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that increases the gap between the age at which women marry and the age at which they have their first child.
The survey found that the higher the level of education, the later they get married and have their first child.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with primary and higher education respectively became mothers for the first time at an average age of 25.1 and 32.1 years.
 Another distinction is also made between women, according to their level of education.
While those with a primary education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those with a secondary education reverse this pattern and prioritise the acquisition of a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child", says Ms Delgado.
