Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As was the case with the anti-lock brake system ABS and as will be the case with ESP, emergency brake assist systems will be a mandatory feature on European cars.
The new rules are already mandatory for newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a grace period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure, imposed by the European Union, is to improve the protection of pedestrians, although, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear-end collisions.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system through the driver's foot.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure on until the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, one third of drivers involved in an accident had failed to apply the brake before the collision, and half had not used the full force of the brake.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The assistance intervention, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with these features, up to 1 100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularisation of the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four accidents involving injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system which, by means of a radar or camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he/she will help by increasing the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimise damage.
