After the rosy days of last spring, when asset inflation dominated the markets, uncertainty is again on the rise, which is not surprising since this is the natural state of affairs in an environment where agents make decisions about a future that is inherently uncertain.
The remedy used by central banks to stabilise markets has been to monetize debt by directly buying assets and indirectly by providing ample liquidity at near-zero rates so that financial institutions can buy assets to mobilise.
The central banks have already confirmed that the direct asset purchases are virtually complete and, without calling into question their non-compliant liquidity policy, are starting to put a little sand in the wheels, as the ECB has done, with their one-year tender next week.
As a result, investors are doubtful about the ability of the global economy to sustain economic recovery without heterodox measures and we are seeing a reversal of the reduction in risk premia.
Stock market volatility and corporate bond spreads are rising again, although they are still far from the paranormal levels they reached at the beginning of the year.
The States have been forced to socialize private risk and public debt is once again affected.
There is again a rush towards quality and the US, Japan and Germany have been the investment havens chosen by investors, leading to a widening of the differences between the euro area countries and Germany.
Spain was barely affected by this episode of instability, but then Standard & Poor's threatened to further revise the rating of the Kingdom of Spain downwards.
On the other hand, a little uncertainty is not bad to silence the defenders of moral hazard, who were again trying to provoke a case of conscience among the global economic policy makers who had restrained the destructive effects of credit restraint on job destruction, when what they should do is decree a new Thanksgiving.
However, the situation in Dubai looks like a tribal struggle between the emirates to regain its place in power in the emirates and we have already seen the case of Greece.
A government that hides a public deficit, elections, and a new government that finds out the pot of roses.
Prodi did it in Italy after Berlusconi and Socrates in Portugal after Durão Barroso.
It would be completely irrational for ECOFIN to bail out Hungary for non-compliance with its external payments at the beginning of the year and allow a member country of the eurozone to default on its commitments.
What is logical, however, is that the Ecofin has encouraged the Greek government to be transparent and makes its citizens co-responsible for the need for extraordinary measures to maintain the stability of its public finances.
If, as we hope, we are faced with an episode of normalisation of transitional risk premia, after some excesses in high positions, this would be foreseeable.
In the Spanish case, as long as our public debt gaps increase as European corporate debt increases, we have nothing to worry about.
If European disparities were to decline and ours to continue to increase, then there would be an idiosyncratic Spanish risk.
The Standard & Poor's case is an anecdote: when our forecasts force most of the research services to anticipate their recovery models and to revise their 2011 forecasts upwards, with the OECD and the European Commission also coming back with a Japanese model for the Spanish economy, it does not give much hope for their warning.
Again, this seems to be an excellent opportunity to buy Spanish assets, even if for the moment prudence is the mother of security.
