Spain, on the other hand, is only third in the world in terms of money earned by the Champions League, although it has won more titles than any other country (five, while Italy has won four, England three and Germany two).
Distribution of
This apparent paradox is explained by the complex procedure for allocating the money used by UEFA.
This year, the organisation, chaired by Michel Platini, expects to earn €1.09 billion through the Champions League.
Of this amount, UEFA will spend 413.1 million on fixed payments: each of the 20 clubs that participated in the qualifying matches (including Atlético de Madrid) received 2.1 million.
In addition, those who managed to participate received 3.8 million just to be there, in addition to more than 550,000 euros for each game played.
There is also a bonus for a win (800 000 euros) and a draw (400 000 for each team).Those who reach the round of eight receive three million each, the eight teams that reach the quarter-finals receive 3.3 million.
The last four teams will each receive $4 million.
And the winner will win $9 million, compared to the other finalist's $5.2 million.
Thus, in the case of fixed payments, a club will earn at least 7,1 million, and at most 31,2 million.
On the other hand, Barça were awarded €2.5 million for winning the European Super Cup in August.
But then there are the variable payments, which are worth 337.8 million.
This money is distributed according to the proportional value of each TV market.
The Spanish market is one of the largest, with four places.
The previous year's champion pockets 40 percent of the money allocated, 30 percent for the runner-up, 20 percent for the third and 10 percent for the fourth.
The other part will be paid according to the number of matches played in the current year's edition.
