New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, the garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have been damaged are taken to a garage, where an expert must assess the damage and the cost of repairs.
Each accident is different, and calculating the cost of parts and the time required for manpower can be a long and complex task.
Calculating by hand the cost of a repair between EUR 20 000 and EUR 30 000, including parts and labour, can take two or three hours.
However, with the help of the latest computer tools, this would be a matter of minutes.
This is why almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
The providers of claims and maintenance services and solutions are dedicated to collecting information from manufacturers, then processing it and offering it to their customers as a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American Solera group, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
The other companies competing in the field of assessment tools and the production of sector information are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company has 63 manufacturers and importers in Spain, each of whom provides information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is constantly increasing, so that in the last five years more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the previous 15 years.
When a new car comes on the market, these companies get down to work.
This is a very difficult job, because you have to catalogue each of the thousand parts of the vehicle and write down its price.
In addition, a  intelligent  graphic image of each model is created, which can be clicked on to identify the different parts of a passenger car.
If it is a mass-selling model, the work can be done in a week if the process proceeds very quickly.
If it is a car with low sales, it may take three or four months.Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
For example, among the most exclusive models, they have information on Porsches, but not on Ferraris or Lamborghinis.
For vehicles in use, the figure is over 99%.
Audatex has eight centres around the world (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) for the documentation and development of the databases, each of which is specialised in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas, Madrid.
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests $90 million a year to build these databases.
Each month, 2.5 million data items are logged, and customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this huge flow of information enables these companies to use it for different purposes and to offer a variety of products.
The most common application is for repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for the management of scrap parts or for calculating the fair value or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide to the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex doesn't offer it in our country, but they do it in the United States.
The products offered by Audatex give an idea of the kind of support it can provide to professionals in the sector.
The company offers ten different tools, the flagship product being AudaPlus, the standard claim assessment solution for experts.
These include cars, motorcycles, light and heavy commercial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it takes into account the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the paint shop.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is €5.75 for customers who use it only rarely, up to 10 times a month.
Then each insurance company, which carries out thousands of tests, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the complete identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it left the assembly line, just by its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle glass, and AudaSubastas is an open server for the professional sector on the Internet which allows bidding on vehicles declared wrecks.
Its statistics service is very useful for identifying trends, carrying out geo-demographic analyses or for identifying common problems by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a particular brand have been taken to the garage for a breakdown or how many have suffered serious accidents for a given period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tool.
It markets, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and provides digital images, as well as access to the official parts, prices and times of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of claims, breakdowns or maintenance of buildings.
The GT Guide to Evaluation is a historical reference product on the market.
The company works with 24 000 users in garages, 3 100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its turnover has increased at a rate of 20% per year over the last three years, and it had a turnover of EUR 10.8 million in 2008.
At the beginning of last year, it started its internationalisation process by setting up an office in Paris.
Audatex was founded in Germany in 1966 and established itself in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its turnover is generated in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America.
The Solera group's worldwide turnover (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) will amount to USD 557 million, 3.3% more than in 2008.
In Spain, the company will receive €19.1 million, up 7.2% on last year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was listed for $1,000 million, today its shares are valued at a total of $2,400 million.
Since 2007, it has been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and is a component of the Standard & Poor's benchmark index.
Internet auctions of crashed cars
Last October, the Solera group bought Autoonline, an Internet platform for the sale of cars, motorcycles and special vehicles involved in accidents.
The operation involved a cost of EUR 59.5 million for 85% of the company's capital, which could be increased to the remaining 15% next year.
The aim of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of accessing a huge international market.
This valuation and sales service is exclusively for professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, garages, cashiers and professional salesmen who must be registered before they can start trading.
The platform was set up in Germany in 1996 and manages more than 650,000 transactions across Europe, including 500,000 in Germany.
Its main markets include Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
There are currently over 1500 sellers and 4000 registered experts on the site.
It manages 3,000 ads per day and in the Spanish market, 100 new ads are published every day.
Under Spanish law, a car with its number plate removed cannot be driven again, but some parts that are not damaged can be used as spare parts.
Collector cars can be re-registered, even though they have been withdrawn, after complex procedures.
Four-step design for a garage
With the Auda-Taller tool, Audatex ensures that the user obtains a quote in just four steps: identifying the vehicle, looking for the spare part, creating a quote and generating it.
The ease of use is a key element of these systems, especially to convince older professionals who, to a greater or lesser extent, are resistant to the use of new management techniques.
The database contains 1 034 vehicles, including 666 tourist vehicles, 109 off-road vehicles, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Of course, to use it, you need a computer and an Internet connection.
Once the model to be repaired has been identified by its chassis number, a real graphic image of the model in question appears and the person selects the part needed.
The user can include variables such as labour costs, increases or reductions, and then print the quote to give to the customer.
AudaTaller is not an estimation tool like AudaPlus, but a reference catalogue.
The main difference between these two systems is that the one for garages does not include estimated man-hours.
The cost of using this tool for the garage is 350 euros per year, which may be credited.
Audatex is currently working to make these images three dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics are very pleased with, as it will allow, for example, to select a door and rotate it to see the inside.
